## Task
Set up alerting based on thresholds defined in the plan.

## Alert Thresholds

| Metric | Threshold | Action |
|--------|-----------|--------|
| Google API error rate | >5% for 5min | Page on-call, enable degraded mode |
| Search P95 latency | >2s for 10min | Warning notification |
| Daily API cost | >$X (configurable) | Alert + emergency throttling |
| Cache hit rate | <50% for 1hr | Investigate |
| Review spam flags | >10/hour | Alert moderation team |

## Implementation Options
1. **Convex cron + webhooks**: Check thresholds periodically, send to Slack/Discord
2. **Sentry alerts**: Use Sentry's alerting for error rate spikes
3. **Custom notification system**: Store alerts in Convex, show in admin UI

## Recommended Approach
Combine Sentry for errors + custom Convex-based alerting for business metrics:

```typescript
// convex/alerts.ts
export const checkAlerts = internalMutation({
  handler: async (ctx) => {
    const errorRate = await getRecentErrorRate(ctx, 'google_api', 5);
    if (errorRate > 0.05) {
      await sendAlert(ctx, {
        severity: 'critical',
        title: 'Google API error rate >5%',
        action: 'Degraded mode activated',
      });
      await ctx.runMutation(internal.serviceMode.setMode, { mode: 2 });
    }
    // ... more checks
  },
});

// Run every minute
crons.interval('check_alerts', { minutes: 1 }, internal.alerts.checkAlerts);
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All threshold alerts configured
- [ ] Notifications reaching appropriate channels
- [ ] Auto-mitigation triggering where specified
- [ ] Alert history viewable in admin

## Task
Configure Sentry for observability with critical safeguards to prevent provider content from appearing in error reports.

## Commands
```bash
npm install @sentry/nextjs
npx @sentry/wizard@latest -i nextjs
```

## Why Redaction is Critical
Provider content (place names, addresses, ratings) must NEVER appear in:
- Error messages
- Breadcrumbs
- Context data
- Stack traces

This is a policy compliance requirement, not optional.

## Configuration
```typescript
// sentry.client.config.ts
Sentry.init({
  beforeSend(event) {
    // Redact any provider content from error
    return redactProviderContent(event);
  },
  beforeBreadcrumb(breadcrumb) {
    // Filter breadcrumbs that might contain provider data
    if (breadcrumb.category === 'fetch') {
      // Redact URLs/bodies for provider endpoints
    }
    return breadcrumb;
  },
});
```

## Redaction Patterns
- Any data from places.googleapis.com responses
- Photo references in URLs
- Place details (name, address, phone, etc.)

## What IS Allowed
- placeKey / place_id (identifiers only)
- Error codes and status
- Latency measurements
- User IDs (if consented)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Sentry capturing errors
- [ ] beforeSend redaction working
- [ ] Breadcrumb filtering working
- [ ] Test that provider content doesn't appear

## Task
Create the central ProviderGateway that all provider access flows through. This is the enforcement point for policy compliance.

## Why Central Gateway
Without a single gateway:
- Budget/rate limits can be bypassed
- Logging might capture provider content differently
- Feature flags might not be respected consistently

## Core Responsibilities
1. **Field mask registry** - Only pre-approved masks, no ad-hoc
2. **Budget enforcement** - Per-endpoint class limits
3. **Circuit breaker integration** - Respect breaker state
4. **Metrics emission** - Latency, error code, cost class, cache outcome
5. **Response redaction** - Strip provider content from logs/errors
6. **Localization defaults** - languageCode, regionCode

## Field Mask Registry
```typescript
// convex/fieldSets.ts
export const FIELD_SETS = {
  SEARCH_LITE: 'id,displayName,location',
  PLACE_HEADER: 'id,displayName,formattedAddress,location',
  PLACE_DETAILS_FULL: 'id,displayName,formattedAddress,location,regularOpeningHours,...',
  HEALTH_CHECK: 'id',
} as const;
```

## Gateway Interface
```typescript
// convex/providerGateway.ts
export async function providerRequest<T>(
  ctx: ActionCtx,
  endpoint: ProviderEndpoint,
  params: ProviderParams,
  options: GatewayOptions
): Promise<ProviderResult<T>> {
  // 1. Check feature flags
  // 2. Check budget
  // 3. Check circuit breaker
  // 4. Apply field mask from registry
  // 5. Apply localization defaults
  // 6. Execute with timeout
  // 7. Emit metrics
  // 8. Return (never log response body)
}
```

## Localization Defaults
- languageCode: from user locale ('ar' | 'fr' | 'en')
- regionCode: 'MA' unless browsing another country

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All provider calls go through gateway
- [ ] Field masks from registry only
- [ ] Metrics emitted for every call
- [ ] Response bodies never logged

## Task
Implement circuit breaker pattern to prevent cascade failures when the provider is having issues.

## States
1. **Closed** (normal) - Requests flow through
2. **Open** - After threshold failures, reject immediately, serve stale cache
3. **Half-Open** - After cooldown, allow one test request

## Thresholds
- Open after: 5 consecutive failures OR 50% error rate in 1 minute
- Half-open after: 30 seconds in Open state
- Close after: 1 successful request in Half-Open

## Implementation
```typescript
// convex/circuitBreaker.ts
interface CircuitBreakerState {
  state: 'closed' | 'open' | 'half_open';
  failureCount: number;
  lastFailureAt: number;
  lastSuccessAt: number;
  openedAt?: number;
}

export async function withCircuitBreaker<T>(
  ctx: ActionCtx,
  serviceKey: string,
  operation: () => Promise<T>,
  fallback?: () => Promise<T>
): Promise<T> {
  const state = await getState(ctx, serviceKey);

  if (state.state === 'open') {
    if (shouldTryHalfOpen(state)) {
      // Allow test request
    } else {
      // Reject immediately, use fallback
      return fallback?.() ?? throwCircuitOpen();
    }
  }

  try {
    const result = await operation();
    await recordSuccess(ctx, serviceKey);
    return result;
  } catch (error) {
    await recordFailure(ctx, serviceKey, error);
    throw error;
  }
}
```

## Integration with Service Modes
- Circuit breaker open → triggers Mode 2 (Provider-Limited)
- Mode manager subscribes to breaker state changes

## Metrics
- breaker_state_changes (counter)
- breaker_rejections (counter)
- breaker_half_open_success_rate (gauge)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] State machine transitions correctly
- [ ] Fallback triggered when open
- [ ] Half-open test requests working
- [ ] Metrics tracking state changes

## Task
Implement singleflight pattern to coalesce identical in-flight provider requests within the same server instance.

## Problem
Without singleflight:
- 20 users open same place → 20 provider calls
- Popular restaurant gets mobbed → stampede
- Map pan with concurrent users → amplified load

## Solution
Coalesce identical requests keyed by request signature:

### Request Signatures
- Details: `{placeId, fieldSet, language, region}`
- Search: `{query, bounds, filters, fieldSet, language, region}`
- Photos: `{photoRef, size}`

## Implementation
```typescript
// lib/singleflight.ts
const inFlight = new Map<string, Promise<any>>();

export async function singleflight<T>(
  key: string,
  operation: () => Promise<T>
): Promise<T> {
  const existing = inFlight.get(key);
  if (existing) {
    return existing as Promise<T>;
  }

  const promise = operation().finally(() => {
    inFlight.delete(key);
  });

  inFlight.set(key, promise);
  return promise;
}
```

## Key Generation
```typescript
function detailsKey(params: DetailsParams): string {
  return `details:${params.placeId}:${params.fieldSet}:${params.language}:${params.region}`;
}
```

## Considerations
- Works per server instance (not distributed)
- For Convex Actions, consider using a short-TTL cache for distributed coalescing
- Don't coalesce if responses are user-specific

## Metrics
- singleflight_hits (counter) - Request coalesced
- singleflight_misses (counter) - New request started

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Identical concurrent requests share one upstream call
- [ ] Different requests not incorrectly coalesced
- [ ] Metrics showing coalescing effectiveness

## Task
Implement budget enforcement that tracks and limits spend per endpoint class (autocomplete/search/details/photos).

## Why Per-Endpoint Budgets
Different endpoints have different costs and importance:
- Autocomplete: Many calls, cheap per call
- Details: Fewer calls, variable cost by field mask
- Photos: Bandwidth-heavy, can be disabled first

## Budget Structure
```typescript
interface EndpointBudget {
  endpoint: 'autocomplete' | 'search' | 'details' | 'photos';
  dailyLimit: number;      // Max calls per day
  currentCount: number;
  costPerCall: number;     // Estimated cost for tracking
  lastResetAt: number;
}
```

## Enforcement Logic
```typescript
async function checkBudget(
  ctx: ActionCtx,
  endpoint: EndpointClass
): Promise<BudgetResult> {
  const budget = await getBudget(ctx, endpoint);

  if (budget.currentCount >= budget.dailyLimit) {
    return { allowed: false, reason: 'budget_exceeded' };
  }

  // Warn at thresholds
  const usage = budget.currentCount / budget.dailyLimit;
  if (usage > 0.8) {
    await emitWarning(ctx, endpoint, usage);
  }

  return { allowed: true };
}
```

## Auto-Mitigation on Budget Exceeded
When budget hits limit:
1. Photos disabled first (most expensive, least critical)
2. Open-now filter disabled (requires extra calls)
3. Max results reduced
4. Eventually trigger Mode 1 (Cost-Saver)

## Integration with Feature Flags
Budget watchdog cron job:
- Runs every 5 minutes
- Checks all endpoint budgets
- Flips feature flags when thresholds crossed

## Metrics
- budget_usage_percent (gauge by endpoint)
- budget_exceeded_events (counter)
- budget_auto_mitigation_triggers (counter)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Per-endpoint tracking working
- [ ] Limits enforced
- [ ] Warnings at 80%
- [ ] Auto-mitigation triggering

## Task
Implement priority-based load shedding to protect critical user actions under load.

## Priority Classes (highest to lowest)
1. **P1: Place details** - Explicit user click, highest intent
2. **P2: Search results** - Explicit search submit
3. **P3: Autocomplete** - Typing, can degrade gracefully
4. **P4: Photos + 'more results'** - Nice to have, shed first

## Load Shedding Strategy
When under pressure (approaching limits):
1. Queue P4 requests, shed if queue grows
2. Rate limit P3 more aggressively
3. P1 and P2 always prioritized

## Implementation
```typescript
// convex/providerGateway.ts
interface RequestOptions {
  priority: 1 | 2 | 3 | 4;
  canShed: boolean;
  fallback?: () => Promise<any>;
}

async function maybeShd(
  ctx: ActionCtx,
  options: RequestOptions
): Promise<'proceed' | 'shed'> {
  const load = await getCurrentLoad(ctx);

  if (load.level === 'critical' && options.priority >= 3) {
    return 'shed';
  }
  if (load.level === 'high' && options.priority === 4) {
    return 'shed';
  }
  return 'proceed';
}
```

## Bulkhead Configuration
- Max 25 concurrent provider calls per region
- Separate queues per priority class
- P4 queue has max depth (drop when full)

## User Experience When Shed
- Autocomplete: Show cached/recent suggestions only
- Photos: Show placeholder + 'Loading...'
- More results: 'Load more' button disabled temporarily

## Metrics
- requests_by_priority (counter)
- requests_shed_by_priority (counter)
- queue_depth_by_priority (gauge)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Priority classes respected under load
- [ ] P4 sheds before P1/P2 affected
- [ ] User-visible fallbacks working
- [ ] Metrics tracking shed rate

## Task
Create compliance regression tests that act as CI gates - failures block deployment.

## Why This is Critical
Accidental policy violations can happen through:
- Developer adding logging statement
- Analytics event including wrong fields
- Next.js route missing no-store directive
- Client storage accidentally caching provider data

These tests catch violations before they reach production.

## Test Categories

### 1. No Provider Content in Persistence
```typescript
test('provider response never written to Convex', async () => {
  // Mock a provider response with restricted content
  const providerResponse = {
    displayName: 'Cafe Clock',
    formattedAddress: '123 Medina...',
    // ... more restricted fields
  };

  // Trigger the flow that processes this
  await processPlaceSearch(providerResponse);

  // Assert that restricted fields are not in DB
  const dbRecords = await getAllPlaceRecords();
  for (const record of dbRecords) {
    expect(record).not.toHaveProperty('displayName');
    expect(record).not.toHaveProperty('formattedAddress');
    // Only placeKey, lat, lng (with expiry) allowed
  }
});
```

### 2. No Provider Content in Analytics
```typescript
test('analytics events use placeKey only', async () => {
  const events = captureAnalyticsEvents(() => {
    trackPlaceView(placeData);
  });

  for (const event of events) {
    expect(event.properties.placeKey).toBeDefined();
    expect(event.properties.name).toBeUndefined();
    expect(event.properties.address).toBeUndefined();
  }
});
```

### 3. Provider Routes are no-store
```typescript
test('place detail route has no-store', async () => {
  const response = await fetch('/place/g/ChIJ...');
  expect(response.headers.get('cache-control'))
    .toContain('no-store');
});
```

### 4. No Provider Content in Sentry
```typescript
test('Sentry events redact provider content', () => {
  const event = createTestSentryEvent({
    extra: { providerResponse: { displayName: 'Test' } }
  });

  const filtered = beforeSend(event);
  expect(filtered.extra.providerResponse).toBeUndefined();
});
```

## CI Integration
These tests run on every PR. Any failure = blocked merge.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All four test categories implemented
- [ ] Tests running in CI
- [ ] Failures blocking deployment
- [ ] Clear error messages explaining violation

## Task
Set up Next.js internationalization for Arabic, French, and English.

## Configuration

### next.config.js
```javascript
module.exports = {
  i18n: {
    locales: ['ar', 'fr', 'en'],
    defaultLocale: 'en',
    localeDetection: true,
  },
};
```

## Directory Structure
```
lib/i18n/
├── locales/
│   ├── ar.json
│   ├── fr.json
│   └── en.json
├── useTranslation.ts
└── config.ts
```

## Translation Keys Structure
```json
{
  "common": {
    "search": "Search",
    "favorites": "Favorites",
    "reviews": "Reviews"
  },
  "home": {
    "nearMe": "Near me",
    "cityPicks": "Popular cities"
  },
  "place": {
    "whatToOrder": "What to order",
    "reviews": "Reviews"
  }
}
```

## Hook Implementation
```typescript
// lib/i18n/useTranslation.ts
export function useTranslation() {
  const locale = useLocale();
  const messages = useMemo(() => loadMessages(locale), [locale]);

  const t = useCallback((key: string, params?: Record<string, string>) => {
    const value = get(messages, key) || key;
    return params ? interpolate(value, params) : value;
  }, [messages]);

  return { t, locale };
}
```

